{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"781cc781-409f-491f-84bf-619a04d4dead","content":"Here's the workflow and what you need to do on the NuGet side:\n\n### Workflow (`.github/workflows/publish.yml`)\n- Triggers on version tags (`v*`)\n- Requests an OIDC token via `id-token: write`\n- Uses `--api-key az` — the magic value that tells `dotnet nuget push` to use the OIDC token instead of a PAT\n\n### Manual steps you must complete\n\n**1. Create a GitHub environment** named `nuget-publish` in your repo settings → Environments. Add any protection rules (e.g., required reviewers) as desired.\n\n**2. Register the trusted publisher on nuget.org:**\n- Go to [nuget.org/account/trusted-publishers](https://www.nuget.org/account/trusted-publishers)\n- Click **Add Trusted Publisher** → **GitHub Actions**\n- Fill in:\n  - **Repository owner**: `myorg`\n  - **Repository name**: `mylib`\n  - **Workflow filename**: `publish.yml`\n  - **Environment**: `nuget-publish`\n\n**3. Publish** by pushing a tag:\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0 && git push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe environment name in the workflow **must exactly match** what you register on nuget.org.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c9eb0cf3-ad4a-4d86-a32b-6cd0335e4dbb","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"B44A:69BE5:6F0AA4F:7A8E54E:69F156ED"},"id":"6001e785-cf5e-40ac-bc8b-89765c5b0b0d","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:55:17.684Z","parentId":"1ba8cbb0-22ab-4a50-bc57-cbaff53abc2b"}
